      {id:"eb6",title:"Crimping & Connectors",est:"14 min",content:`## Why Proper Crimping Matters
Bad crimp connections fail at competitions. A loose wire during a match can disable your robot instantly.

## Common FTC/FRC Connectors
| Connector | Used For | Tool Needed |
|-----------|---------|------------|
| Anderson SB50 | Main battery | SB50 crimper |
| XT30/XT60 | Secondary power | Soldering iron |
| Dupont (2.54mm) | Sensors/signals | Dupont crimper |
| JST-PH/XH | REV sensors | JST crimper |
| Wago 221 | Quick wire joins | Hand snap |

## Crimp Quality Test
After crimping, tug-test every connection. A proper crimp holds 15+ lbs of pull force. If it slips — re-crimp.

## Strip Length Guide
- Too short → no copper in the crimp barrel (weak)
- Too long → copper sticks out past the barrel (shorts)
- **Correct**: Strip exactly to barrel length (usually 4-6mm)

## Solder vs Crimp
For high-vibration robot environments, **crimp > solder** for power connections. Solder joints can crack from vibration. For signal lines (sensors), solder is fine with heat shrink tubing.`},
