      {id:"mi7",title:"Elevator & Lift Systems",est:"19 min",content:`## The Vertical Challenge
Lifts move game pieces up. They're mechanically challenging but strategically essential in most FTC/FRC games.

## Lift Types
**Single-stage linear slide**: Simple, low height gain (1:1 extension)
**Continuous rigging**: Rope/cable systems, 2:1 or 3:1 extension ratio
**Cascade (stacked)**: Stages extend sequentially, highest extension per stage
**Scissor lift**: Compact when folded, expands to significant height

## Rigging Patterns
Most FTC teams use 2-stage or 3-stage continuous slides.
- String path: spool → fixed pulley → moving carriage → fixed anchor
- Each stage doubles height: 4" travel → 8" with 2 stages, 12" with 3
- Use Dyneema or spectra line — doesn't stretch under load

## Counterbalancing (critical)
Without counterbalance: motor fights gravity the entire way up.
With a constant-force spring matched to arm weight: motor only accelerates/decelerates.
Result: 50% less current draw, faster movement, less heating.

## Common Problems & Fixes
| Problem | Cause | Fix |
|---------|-------|-----|
| Slides bind | Misalignment | Check carriage squareness, adjust bearing preload |
| String slips | Wrong anchor | Use cable clamp, not just a knot |
| Oscillates at top | No D-term | Add kD to PID, reduce kP |
| Drops on power loss | No brake | Enable brake mode, add mechanical stop |`},
