      {id:"eb7",title:"Multimeter Basics",est:"12 min",content:`## The Multimeter: Fastest Debugging Tool
A multimeter diagnoses almost every electrical problem in minutes. Learn five measurements and you can fix most faults.

## DC Voltage (most used)
Set dial to DC Voltage (20V range).
Red probe to +, black to ground.
Read battery: 12.6V+ (full) · 11V (low) · < 10V (replace now)

## Continuity Test (beep mode)
Tells you if electricity can flow between two points.
Beep = connected path. No beep = broken wire or blown fuse.
Uses: check fuses, test crimped connectors, trace broken wires.

## Resistance (Ω)
Disconnect from circuit first!
Motor winding resistance: 0.5–5Ω (if ∞, coil is broken)

## Diagnosing Common Problems
| Symptom | Test | Result Meaning |
|---------|------|---------------|
| Motor dead | Continuity at motor terminals | No beep = bad motor or wiring |
| Fuse blown? | Continuity across fuse | No beep = blown, replace it |
| Battery dead? | Voltage at battery terminals | < 10V = replace battery |
| Servo doesn't respond | Voltage at servo power rail | Should read ~5V |
| Encoder skips | Voltage at encoder power | Should be 3.3V or 5V |

## Pro Tips
- Always check connections at both ends of a wire
- Wiggle connectors while testing — intermittent faults only show when moving
- Label your probes (some cheap meters are wrong colors)`},
