      {id:"ei7",title:"CAN Bus & Network Communication",est:"20 min",content:`## What Is CAN Bus?
Controller Area Network (CAN) is a serial bus that lets every device share a single two-wire network instead of individual signal wires. FRC robots use CAN for Talon SRX, Spark MAX, Falcon 500, and many sensors.

## CAN vs PWM
| Feature | CAN | PWM |
|---------|-----|-----|
| Wires per device | 2 (shared bus) | 3 (per device) |
| Status feedback | Full telemetry | None |
| Fault detection | Yes | No |
| Configuration | Software | Hardware jumper |
| Max devices | 62 | ~20 practical |

## CAN Wiring
- Yellow wire = CAN-High, Green wire = CAN-Low
- Daisy-chain from roboRIO CAN port through all devices
- Terminate with 120Ω resistor at each END of chain
- Missing termination = intermittent CAN faults

## CAN ID Assignment
Each device needs a unique ID (1–62).
In Phoenix Tuner X (Talons) or REV Hardware Client (Spark MAX):
1. Connect via USB
2. Set CAN ID — start at 1 for drivetrains
3. Confirm it appears on CAN bus before disconnecting
4. Label the physical motor controller with its ID

## Diagnosing CAN Problems
- Driver Station shows "CAN Utilization" — should be < 70%
- Devices blinking alternating colors = CAN fault
- Check termination resistors first, then connections, then IDs`},
