      {id:"si7",title:"Scouting System Design",est:"17 min",content:`## Building a Scouting System from Scratch
Great scouting systems have three layers: collection, storage, and analysis.

## Collection Layer
**What data matters?**
- Auto: specific actions completed (not just score)
- Teleop: cycles per minute, scoring locations used
- Endgame: attempted, succeeded, time taken
- Defense: did they play it, were they effective?
- Reliability: 1–5 scale, mechanical issues noted

**Collection tools:**
- Paper forms (low-tech, reliable, offline)
- Google Forms → Sheets (free, easy analysis)
- Custom app (most powerful, your web dev skills apply here)

## Storage Layer
6 scouts × 12 quals = 72 scouting records minimum.
At a regional: 6 scouts × 72 matches × 3 robots = ~200 entries needed.

Store: team, match, scout name, all metrics, timestamp

## Analysis Layer
\`\`\`
Per-team stats:
  avg_auto = mean(auto_score)
  consistency = 1 - std(total)/mean(total)
  weighted_score = (auto * 1.5) + teleop + (endgame * 2)
  combined_score = weighted_score * consistency
\`\`\`
Combined score rewards both high performance AND reliability.

## Red Flags in Data
- Team has > 30% variance in score = unreliable
- Score drops significantly in later matches = battery/mechanical issues
- Big gap between scouted and official score = data quality problem`},
