      {id:"sa7",title:"Eliminations Strategy",est:"19 min",content:`## Quals vs Elims: Different Games
Everything changes in eliminations. Winning matches is the only goal — ranking points and experimentation are irrelevant.

## Alliance Selection Psychology
Captains select based on: your robot's capabilities, your reliability, and how well you complement their robot.

Be ready to answer in the pit:
- "What can your robot do reliably?" (not what it does sometimes)
- "Do you have any known mechanical issues?"
- "What do you need from alliance partners?"

## Pre-Elim Alliance Strategy Meeting (7 minutes)
1. Starting positions (agree who goes where) — 1 min
2. Auto routines — what does each robot run, can any combine? — 2 min
3. Teleop zones — who owns which field area? — 1 min
4. Endgame timing — countdown, abort signal — 1 min
5. Emergency plan — if a robot dies, what changes? — 1 min
6. Questions from drive teams — 1 min

## Score Differential Decisions (Last 30 Seconds)
- Up 15+: protect lead, early endgame
- Up 5–14: one offensive robot, two protect
- Down 1–14: max offense AND endgame, need both
- Down 15+: only way back is opponent penalty — clean play, hope

## Drive Team Communication
Simple codewords agreed before match:
- "Park" = go to endgame position now
- "Chase" = go for high-value scoring
- "Box" = play defense on [color][number]
- "Clear" = stop defending, return to offense`},
