      {id:"fi4",title:"Corporate Outreach Campaigns",est:"15 min",content:`## Running a Systematic Outreach Campaign
One sponsor letter sent to one company is an ask. Fifty letters sent to fifty companies with follow-up is a campaign.

## Building Your Target List
Start with 50–100 companies. Prioritize:
1. Companies within 10 miles (local connection matters)
2. Companies in STEM/manufacturing sectors
3. Companies where team members' parents work (warm leads)
4. Companies that sponsor other local nonprofits (proven givers)

## The 5-Touch Outreach Sequence
\`\`\`
Day 0:  Send personalized email/letter
Day 7:  Follow-up call ("Did you receive our letter?")
Day 14: Second email with a specific ask and deadline
Day 21: Call decision maker directly (not front desk)
Day 30: Final email — "We're finalizing sponsors this week"
\`\`\`
Most sponsors say yes between touches 2 and 4.

## Call Script
"Hi, this is [Name] from Team 1234, a FIRST Robotics team at [School].
We sent you a letter last week about our sponsorship program.
I'm calling to see if [Company] might be interested in supporting
our team this season. We're looking for a [Bronze/Silver/Gold] sponsor.
Do you have two minutes to discuss?"

Keep it under 90 seconds. Be confident — you're offering them value, not begging.

## Tracking Your Pipeline
Use a spreadsheet with columns:
Company | Contact | Date Sent | Date Called | Response | Status | Amount
Color-code by status: Not contacted, Contacted, Interested, Committed, Declined`},
