      {id:"ji13",title:"Finite State Machines for Autonomous",est:"25 min",content:`## Finite State Machines (FSM)

Instead of one long sequence of if-statements, FSMs make autonomous code readable and robust.

### The Problem with Simple Sequences
\`\`\`java
// BAD: hard to modify, breaks if one step fails
drive(30);
turn(90);
drop();
drive(20);
\`\`\`

### FSM Approach
\`\`\`java
enum State { DRIVE_TO_SPIKE, TURN_TO_BACKDROP, PLACE_PIXEL, PARK, IDLE }

State currentState = State.DRIVE_TO_SPIKE;
ElapsedTime timer = new ElapsedTime();

@Override
public void loop() {
    switch (currentState) {
        case DRIVE_TO_SPIKE:
            if (robot.driveToPosition(30, 0.6)) {
                currentState = State.TURN_TO_BACKDROP;
                timer.reset();
            }
            break;
        case TURN_TO_BACKDROP:
            if (robot.turnToHeading(90, 0.4)) {
                currentState = State.PLACE_PIXEL;
            }
            break;
        case PLACE_PIXEL:
            robot.openClaw();
            if (timer.seconds() > 0.5) {
                currentState = State.PARK;
            }
            break;
        case PARK:
            robot.driveToPosition(60, 0.4);
            currentState = State.IDLE;
            break;
        case IDLE:
            break;
    }
}
\`\`\`

### Benefits
- **Easy to add states** — just add a new enum value and case
- **Easy to debug** — you can log which state you're in
- **Non-blocking** — the loop keeps running even while waiting
- **Reusable** — states can be reused across auto routines
