      {id:"sa7",title:"Autonomous Path Planning Strategy",est:"25 min",content:`## Autonomous Strategy

The first 30 seconds of a match are worth disproportionately more than teleop because:
1. Autonomous points often have multipliers
2. Field is uncrowded — no defense
3. Consistency separates elite teams

### Picking Your Auto Routine

**Conservative (High Consistency)**
- Score 1-2 guaranteed elements
- Park in a safe zone
- 90%+ success rate
- Good for unreliable robots or new drivers

**Aggressive (High Ceiling)**
- Score 3+ elements
- Multi-zone paths
- 60-70% success rate
- Only worth it if your robot is reliable

### The 70% Rule
An aggressive auto that scores 2x points but only works 60% of the time is worth less than a conservative auto that works 90% of the time.

Expected value = success rate × points scored

Example:
- Conservative: 0.90 × 20 = **18 expected points**
- Aggressive: 0.65 × 40 = **26 expected points**

In this case, aggressive is worth it. But if success drops to 40%: 0.40 × 40 = 16 — now conservative wins.

### Path Redundancy
Build in fallbacks. If vision fails to detect a target, default to a safe scoring position instead of doing nothing. 

Something > Nothing in autonomous.
