Odometry tracks your robot's position using passive encoder wheels (dead wheels) that always touch the floor.

### Why Dead Wheels?
Regular motor encoders measure motor rotation — but wheels slip. Dead wheels are unpowered, always contacting the floor, so they measure actual travel.

### Two-Wheel Odometry Setup
\`\`\`
Two perpendicular wheels:
- Forward wheel: measures forward/backward movement
- Strafe wheel: measures left/right movement
\`\`\`

### Math — Pose Tracking
\`\`\`java
// Track position as (x, y, heading)
double x = 0, y = 0, heading = 0;

// Each loop:
double deltaForward = (forwardEncoder.getCurrentPosition() - prevForward) / TICKS_PER_INCH;
double deltaStrafe  = (strafeEncoder.getCurrentPosition()  - prevStrafe)  / TICKS_PER_INCH;
double deltaHeading = imu.getAngularOrientation().firstAngle - prevHeading;

// Field-centric update
x += deltaForward * Math.cos(heading) - deltaStrafe * Math.sin(heading);
y += deltaForward * Math.sin(heading) + deltaStrafe * Math.cos(heading);
heading += deltaHeading;

prevForward = forwardEncoder.getCurrentPosition();
prevStrafe  = strafeEncoder.getCurrentPosition();
prevHeading = imu.getAngularOrientation().firstAngle;

telemetry.addData("X", x);
telemetry.addData("Y", y);
telemetry.addData("Heading", Math.toDegrees(heading));
