      {id:"ja13",title:"Multithreading in FTC",est:"30 min",content:`## Multithreading — Do Two Things at Once

In FTC, multithreading lets your robot update sensors or run background tasks without blocking the main loop.

### The Problem
\`\`\`java
// This BLOCKS the whole loop for 500ms:
sleep(500);
// Nothing else can happen during this time!
\`\`\`

### Solution: Background Thread
\`\`\`java
public class SensorThread extends Thread {
    volatile double distance = 0;
    DistanceSensor sensor;
    volatile boolean running = true;

    public SensorThread(DistanceSensor sensor) {
        this.sensor = sensor;
    }

    @Override
    public void run() {
        while (running) {
            distance = sensor.getDistance(DistanceUnit.CM);
            try { Thread.sleep(50); } catch (InterruptedException e) { break; }
        }
    }

    public void stopThread() { running = false; }
}
\`\`\`

### Using It in OpMode
\`\`\`java
SensorThread sensorThread;

@Override public void init() {
    DistanceSensor ds = hardwareMap.get(DistanceSensor.class, "dist");
    sensorThread = new SensorThread(ds);
    sensorThread.start(); // Runs in background
}

@Override public void loop() {
    // Main loop still runs freely
    double dist = sensorThread.distance; // Read latest value
    if (dist < 10) { intake.setPower(0); }

    leftDrive.setPower(-gamepad1.left_stick_y);
}

@Override public void stop() {
    sensorThread.stopThread(); // Always clean up!
}
\`\`\`

### volatile Keyword
\`\`\`java
volatile double distance = 0;
\`\`\`
**volatile** tells Java this variable can change from another thread. Without it, Java might cache a stale value.

### Thread Safety Rules
1. Use **volatile** for simple values shared between threads
2. Use **synchronized** blocks for complex data structures
3. Always call **stopThread()** in stop() to prevent memory leaks
4. Keep threads simple — no UI updates or hardware calls from background threads
