      {id:"mb13",title:"Reading Engineering Drawings",est:"18 min",content:`## Reading Engineering Drawings (Technical Drawings)

Every manufactured part comes with a drawing. Learning to read them lets you order the right parts and build correctly.

### The Three Views
Engineering drawings show three orthogonal views:
\`\`\`
      Top View
         ↑
Left ← [Part] → Right View
         ↓
      Front View
\`\`\`

### Dimensions
Numbers on drawings show size in inches or millimeters:
- **2.500** = 2.5 inches (trailing zeros mean precision)
- **Ø0.500** = hole diameter of 0.5 inches (Ø means diameter)
- **4×** = feature repeated 4 times

### Title Block (Bottom Right Corner)
Every drawing has a title block showing:
- Part name and number
- Material (e.g., 6061-T6 Aluminum)
- Scale (e.g., 1:2 means drawing is half real size)
- Tolerance (e.g., ±0.010 means ±10 thousandths allowed)
- Revision (A, B, C — newer revisions fix errors)

### Tolerances — How Precise?
| Tolerance | What It Means |
|-----------|---------------|
| ±0.100 | Low precision — rough cut OK |
| ±0.010 | Medium — CNC or careful hand work |
| ±0.001 | High — requires precision machining |

### Bill of Materials (BOM)
Many drawings include a parts list:
- Part number, description, quantity, material
- Use this to order everything needed before building

**Pro tip**: When in doubt, measure twice, cut once. A misread drawing wastes expensive material.
