      {id:"ea4",title:"CAN Bus and Smart Motor Controllers",est:"28 min",content:`## CAN Bus — The FRC Electrical Backbone

CAN (Controller Area Network) is a communication protocol that lets motor controllers, sensors, and the roboRIO share data on a two-wire bus.

### Why CAN Over PWM?
| Feature | PWM | CAN |
|---------|-----|-----|
| Wires needed | 3 per device | 2 shared bus |
| Feedback | None | Full telemetry |
| Velocity control | External | Built-in |
| Current limiting | External | Built-in |
| Addresses | None | Each device has ID |

### Wiring CAN Bus
\`\`\`
roboRIO → [CAN H / CAN L] → SPARK MAX → SPARK MAX → SPARK MAX → PDH
                              (ID: 1)      (ID: 2)      (ID: 3)
\`\`\`
Daisy-chain all devices. Terminate the last device with a 120Ω resistor.

### REV SPARK MAX Configuration
\`\`\`java
// Set CAN ID via REV Hardware Client (USB)
// Then use in code:
CANSparkMax motor = new CANSparkMax(1, MotorType.kBrushless); // ID 1

// Velocity control (RPM) — built-in closed loop
SparkMaxPIDController pid = motor.getPIDController();
RelativeEncoder encoder = motor.getEncoder();

pid.setP(0.0001);
pid.setI(0);
pid.setD(0);
pid.setFF(0.000175); // Feedforward for NEO

// Set target: 3000 RPM
pid.setReference(3000, CANSparkMax.ControlType.kVelocity);

// Read actual RPM
double currentRPM = encoder.getVelocity();
\`\`\`

### Current Limiting (Very Important!)
\`\`\`java
motor.setSmartCurrentLimit(40); // Amps — prevents brownouts and motor damage
// Drivetrain: 40A each
// Mechanism motors: 20-30A
// Small mechanisms: 10-15A
\`\`\`

### Status Frames — Reduce CAN Bus Load
\`\`\`java
// Only request data you need — reduces 50% of bus traffic
motor.setPeriodicFramePeriod(CANSparkMax.PeriodicFrame.kStatus0, 10);  // Applied output, faults
motor.setPeriodicFramePeriod(CANSparkMax.PeriodicFrame.kStatus1, 20);  // Velocity, current
motor.setPeriodicFramePeriod(CANSparkMax.PeriodicFrame.kStatus2, 100); // Position (slower is fine)
\`\`\`
