      {id:"sa9",title:"OPR, DPR, and CCWM Explained",est:"22 min",content:`## Advanced Match Statistics

### OPR — Offensive Power Rating
OPR estimates how many points a team contributes per match, calculated by solving a system of linear equations across all match results.

\`\`\`
If Team A + Team B + Team C = 85 points (match 1)
And Team A + Team D + Team E = 72 points (match 2)
...
OPR solves for each team's individual contribution
\`\`\`

**Interpretation:**
- High OPR = high scoring contribution
- OPR is an ESTIMATE — solo testing or defense affect it
- Useful for initial alliance selection sorting

### DPR — Defensive Power Rating
DPR estimates how many points a team's opponents score LESS when that team is in the match.

- High DPR = effective defense player
- Low DPR (negative) = opponents score more — avoid this team on defense

### CCWM — Calculated Contribution to Winning Margin
CCWM = OPR − DPR

The most complete single metric. A team with high CCWM both scores a lot AND prevents opponents from scoring.

### Auto OPR (Auto Points Contribution)
Some scouting platforms calculate Auto OPR separately — crucial because:
- Auto points often have multipliers
- Consistent auto = reliable points even when teleop is inconsistent
- Helps identify teams who are great scorers but have no auto

### Using Stats Wisely
\`\`\`
Don't: rank teams purely by OPR and pick in order
Do: combine OPR with:
  - Consistency (std deviation)
  - Climb rate (% of matches)
  - Auto reliability
  - Your own scouting observations
\`\`\`

Stats describe the past — your scouts observe the present. A team that fixed a bug between events won't show it in stats yet.
