      {id:"sfa2",title:"Pneumatics Safety (FRC)",est:"20 min",content:`## Pneumatics Safety in FRC

Pneumatic systems use compressed air (up to 120 PSI working pressure) to power cylinders and actuators. High pressure means serious safety risks if mishandled.

### FRC Pneumatics Rules
- Max storage pressure: **120 PSI** (stored in tanks)
- Max working pressure: **60 PSI** (after the regulator)
- Relief valve must be set to release at 125 PSI

### Safe Pressure-Up Procedure
1. Ensure all fittings are connected and secure
2. Keep everyone clear of cylinders (they WILL move when pressurized)
3. Turn on compressor gradually — monitor pressure gauge
4. Listen for hissing (air leaks) — shut down if you hear any
5. Verify relief valve pops at correct pressure

### Safe Pressure-Down Procedure
**Before working on pneumatics, ALWAYS bleed the system:**
\`\`\`
1. Disable robot
2. Manually actuate each solenoid valve to exhaust air
3. Verify pressure gauge reads 0 PSI
4. Open the manual bleed valve if available
5. Confirm all cylinders are fully retracted or in safe position
NEVER disconnect a fitting under pressure!
\`\`\`

### Leak Detection
- Use soapy water on fittings — bubbles = leak
- Common leak points: push-to-connect fittings, solenoid valves, cylinder ports
- Never use your hand to feel for leaks (high-pressure air can penetrate skin)

### Cylinder Safety
- Cylinders extend with force — keep fingers, eyes, and faces clear
- Know the cylinder's max force: Force = Pressure × Area
- A 1" bore cylinder at 60 PSI = 47 lbs of force
- Add physical hard stops in CAD so cylinders can't slam mechanisms into the robot

### Solenoid Valves
- Single-acting: spring return when unenergized (safer — returns to known state)
- Double-acting: holds position when unenergized (must account for this in code)
