      {id:"ji19",title:"Linear OpMode vs Iterative OpMode",est:"20 min",content:`## Two Ways to Write FTC OpModes

FTC offers two base classes for OpModes. Choosing the right one matters.

### LinearOpMode — Sequential Programming
\`\`\`java
@TeleOp
public class MyLinear extends LinearOpMode {
    @Override
    public void runOpMode() {
        // Setup
        DcMotor motor = hardwareMap.get(DcMotor.class, "motor");
        waitForStart();

        // Runs once — you control the loop
        while (opModeIsActive()) {
            motor.setPower(-gamepad1.left_stick_y);
            telemetry.update();
        }
    }
}
\`\`\`
**Best for:** Autonomous (sequential steps), beginners learning flow control

### OpMode (Iterative) — Callback-Based
\`\`\`java
@TeleOp
public class MyIterative extends OpMode {
    DcMotor motor;

    @Override
    public void init() {
        motor = hardwareMap.get(DcMotor.class, "motor");
    }

    @Override
    public void loop() {
        // Called ~100 times/sec automatically
        motor.setPower(-gamepad1.left_stick_y);
        telemetry.update();
    }

    @Override
    public void stop() {
        motor.setPower(0); // Called once when STOP pressed
    }
}
\`\`\`
**Best for:** TeleOp, experienced programmers, time-sensitive loops

### Key Differences
| Feature | LinearOpMode | OpMode (Iterative) |
|---------|-------------|-------------------|
| Loop control | You write while() | SDK calls loop() for you |
| sleep() | ✅ Available | ❌ Never use (freezes) |
| Blocking | OK in auto | Never block |
| Best for | Autonomous | TeleOp |

### When to Use Each
- **Just starting out?** → LinearOpMode for everything
- **Complex TeleOp?** → Consider OpMode (Iterative)
- **Autonomous always** → LinearOpMode (sequential steps make sense)
`,quiz:[
