      {id:"ea5",title:"Closed-Loop Arm Control with Gravity Compensation",est:"30 min",content:`## Arm Control — The Hard Problem

Arms that lift against gravity require more than just PID — they need feedforward to hold position without oscillating.

### Why Pure PID Fails for Arms
\`\`\`
Problem: When arm is at 90° (horizontal), gravity pulls it down hard.
         At 0° (vertical up), gravity has no effect.
         Pure PID can't know this — it just sees position error.
\`\`\`

### Gravity Feedforward
\`\`\`java
// Arm angle in radians (0 = vertical, π/2 = horizontal)
double armAngle = (encoder.getCurrentPosition() / TICKS_PER_REV) * 2 * Math.PI;

// Gravity compensation term — cosine because:
// At horizontal (90°): cos(90°) = 1.0 — maximum compensation needed
// At vertical (0°): cos(0°) = 1.0 — wait, vertical UP means no gravity pull...
// Use sin for arms where 0 = stowed, 90 = horizontal:
double kG = 0.15; // Tune this for your arm weight
double gravityFF = kG * Math.cos(armAngle); // cos for horizontal = max gravity

// Combined PIDF output:
double pidOutput = pid.calculate(encoder.getCurrentPosition(), targetTicks);
double totalOutput = pidOutput + gravityFF;
arm.set(totalOutput);
\`\`\`

### Anti-Windup for I Term
\`\`\`java
// Integrator windup: if arm is stuck at limit, I term builds forever
// When you finally move, the arm slams past target
pid.setIntegratorRange(-0.15, 0.15); // SPARK MAX / WPILib
\`\`\`

### Trapezoidal Motion Profile
\`\`\`java
// Instead of jumping to target, ramp velocity smoothly
// WPILib TrapezoidProfile:
TrapezoidProfile.Constraints constraints =
    new TrapezoidProfile.Constraints(300, 200); // max vel, max accel (ticks/s)

TrapezoidProfile profile = new TrapezoidProfile(constraints);
TrapezoidProfile.State goal = new TrapezoidProfile.State(targetTicks, 0);
TrapezoidProfile.State current = new TrapezoidProfile.State(encoder.getPosition(), encoder.getVelocity());

TrapezoidProfile.State setpoint = profile.calculate(0.02, current, goal); // 20ms dt
pid.setReference(setpoint.position, ControlType.kPosition);
\`\`\`
