      {id:"si10",title:"Endgame Optimization",est:"18 min",content:`## Maximizing Endgame Points

Endgame often has the highest point-per-second value in FIRST games. Planning it precisely wins matches.

### Timing Calculation
\`\`\`
Endgame = last 30 seconds of teleop
Climb attempt: typically takes 10-20 seconds

Optimal start time = 30s mark
Leave 5s margin = start at 35s remaining

Trigger: Set a timer or watch the field clock
Your human player can signal you with 30s left
\`\`\`

### The Endgame Decision Tree
\`\`\`
With 35 seconds remaining:

Are we winning by > 15 points?
  YES → Defend the win: park/attempt climb, avoid penalties
  NO  → Can we realistically swing the score?
          YES → Full endgame push
          NO  → Focus on last teleop cycles, attempt climb

Is our climb reliable (>80% success rate)?
  YES → Always attempt
  NO  → Consider park points instead of risking 0
\`\`\`

### Pre-Positioning
The fastest climbs start from the correct position:
- Drive to climb zone BEFORE endgame triggers
- Face the correct direction
- Clear any obstacles beforehand
- Your drive team calls "PREP" at 45 seconds

### Alliance Coordination
Never have two robots trying to climb the same mechanism:
\`\`\`
Example 3-robot plan (FRC chain/stage):
Robot 1: Center climb (fastest, most reliable) → 30s remaining
Robot 2: Right climb → 28s remaining
Robot 3: Backup — park if 1 and 2 succeed, climb if needed

Failure plan: Robot 3 always parks minimum
\`\`\`

### Point Math
Always know the math for your current game:
| Action | Points | Time to complete |
|--------|--------|-----------------|
| Park | 3 | 5s |
| Low climb | 5 | 10s |
| High climb | 15 | 20s |
| Trap | 5 | 8s |
