      {id:"sa10",title:"Scouting System Design",est:"22 min",content:`## Building a Full Scouting System

A good scouting system is the difference between alliance selection based on gut feelings vs real data.

### What Data to Collect
**Per Match (Quantitative):**
- Auto points / did auto work
- Teleop cycles (game pieces per minute)
- Scoring zone(s) used
- Penalties taken
- Climb result (and time)
- Did robot break down?

**Per Match (Qualitative):**
- Defense style and effectiveness
- Driver skill rating
- Robot speed
- Notes on anything unusual

### Minimum Viable Scout Sheet
For busy competitions, collect only:
\`\`\`
Team # | Auto ✓/✗ | Cycles | Climb | Rating | Notes
\`\`\`
(This can be done on paper in 30 seconds per match)

### Sample Size Requirements
| Matches scouted | Confidence level |
|-----------------|-----------------|
| 1 | Very low — could be atypical |
| 2-3 | Low — small sample |
| 4-5 | Medium — reasonable estimate |
| 6+ | High — strong data |

Always scout every team at least 3 times before alliance selection.

### Aggregation and Analysis
\`\`\`python
import pandas as pd

df = pd.read_csv('scout_data.csv')

# Per-team aggregates
summary = df.groupby('team').agg({
    'auto': 'mean',
    'cycles': 'mean',
    'climb_success': 'mean',  # % success
    'rating': 'mean',
    'broke_down': 'sum',  # total breakdowns
}).round(2)

summary['consistency'] = df.groupby('team')['cycles'].std().fillna(0)
print(summary.sort_values('rating', ascending=False).head(20))
