      {id:"jb20",title:"Motor Modes Explained",est:"20 min",content:`## Four Motor Modes in FTC

The FTC SDK gives you four ways to run a motor. Choosing the right mode is essential.

### RUN_WITHOUT_ENCODER
\`\`\`java
// Raw power control — no encoder feedback
motor.setMode(DcMotor.RunMode.RUN_WITHOUT_ENCODER);
motor.setPower(0.8); // just spin at 80% duty cycle
\`\`\`
Use when: You don't care about exact speed or distance. Simplest mode.

### RUN_USING_ENCODER
\`\`\`java
// Encoder-regulated speed control
motor.setMode(DcMotor.RunMode.RUN_USING_ENCODER);
motor.setPower(0.8); // now 80% of MAX_SPEED in ticks/sec
\`\`\`
Use when: You want consistent speed regardless of battery level. Good for shooter flywheels.

### STOP_AND_RESET_ENCODER
\`\`\`java
// Zeros the encoder counter
motor.setMode(DcMotor.RunMode.STOP_AND_RESET_ENCODER);
// Always do this at init to start from a known position
\`\`\`
Use at start of autonomous to reset position tracking.

### RUN_TO_POSITION ← Most Useful for Auto
\`\`\`java
// Set target, run to it, stop automatically
motor.setTargetPosition(1500); // encoder ticks
motor.setMode(DcMotor.RunMode.RUN_TO_POSITION);
motor.setPower(0.6);           // speed (positive always!)

// Wait for completion
while (motor.isBusy() && opModeIsActive()) {
    telemetry.addData("Current", motor.getCurrentPosition());
    telemetry.addData("Target",  motor.getTargetPosition());
    telemetry.update();
}
motor.setPower(0); // Stop when done
\`\`\`

### Mode Sequence for Auto
\`\`\`java
// Correct order every time:
motor.setMode(DcMotor.RunMode.STOP_AND_RESET_ENCODER);  // 1. Zero
motor.setTargetPosition(2000);                           // 2. Set target
motor.setMode(DcMotor.RunMode.RUN_TO_POSITION);          // 3. Enable mode
motor.setPower(0.7);                                     // 4. Start moving
\`\`\`
