      {id:"pyb6",title:"Python for Scouting: Basic Stats",est:"20 min",content:`## Quick Team Stats with Python

You don't need pandas to start analyzing scouting data. Pure Python handles small datasets well.

### Storing Scouting Data
\`\`\`python
# List of dicts — one per match observation
scouting = [
    {"team": 4512, "auto": 15, "teleop": 32, "climb": True,  "cycles": 8},
    {"team": 4512, "auto": 12, "teleop": 28, "climb": True,  "cycles": 7},
    {"team": 4512, "auto":  0, "teleop": 22, "climb": False, "cycles": 5},
    {"team": 1678, "auto": 18, "teleop": 40, "climb": True,  "cycles": 11},
    {"team": 1678, "auto": 18, "teleop": 38, "climb": True,  "cycles": 10},
]
\`\`\`

### Filter by Team
\`\`\`python
def get_team(data, team_number):
    return [e for e in data if e["team"] == team_number]

team_4512 = get_team(scouting, 4512)
print(f"Matches scouted: {len(team_4512)}")
\`\`\`

### Calculate Statistics
\`\`\`python
def team_stats(entries):
    autos   = [e["auto"]   for e in entries]
    teleops = [e["teleop"] for e in entries]
    totals  = [a + t for a, t in zip(autos, teleops)]
    climbs  = [e["climb"]  for e in entries]
    
    return {
        "avg_auto":   round(sum(autos)   / len(autos),   1),
        "avg_teleop": round(sum(teleops) / len(teleops), 1),
        "avg_total":  round(sum(totals)  / len(totals),  1),
        "max_total":  max(totals),
        "climb_rate": round(sum(climbs)  / len(climbs) * 100, 1),
        "matches":    len(entries),
    }

stats = team_stats(team_4512)
print(f"Avg total: {stats['avg_total']} | Climb: {stats['climb_rate']}%")
\`\`\`

### Rank All Teams
\`\`\`python
teams = set(e["team"] for e in scouting)
rankings = []
for team in teams:
    entries = get_team(scouting, team)
    stats = team_stats(entries)
    rankings.append((team, stats["avg_total"]))

rankings.sort(key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)
print("\\nTeam Rankings by Avg Total Score:")
for rank, (team, avg) in enumerate(rankings, 1):
    print(f"  #{rank} — Team {team}: {avg} pts avg")
