      {id:"mi13",title:"Belt and Chain Drive Systems",est:"22 min",content:`## Belt vs Chain Drive

Both transmit power between shafts. Each has strengths that make it better for certain applications.

### Belt Drive

**Advantages:**
- Quiet operation
- No lubrication needed
- Lightweight
- Slightly elastic — absorbs shock loads
- Can run at higher speeds

**Disadvantages:**
- Can slip under very high load
- Must be tensioned correctly
- Can break if misaligned

**Best uses:** High-speed mechanisms (shooters, elevators), anything where noise matters, precise ratio drives

### Chain Drive

**Advantages:**
- Higher load capacity (doesn't slip)
- Forgiving of minor misalignment
- Easy to adjust length (remove/add links)
- Available everywhere (bicycle, hardware store)

**Disadvantages:**
- Noisy
- Requires lubrication (chain lube spray)
- Heavier than belt
- Stretches over time

**Best uses:** Drivetrain, heavy lifts, anywhere slip is unacceptable

### Tension — The Critical Setting
\`\`\`
Belt: 2-3mm deflection at center under light finger pressure
Chain: 3-5mm total slack (too tight = bearing wear, too loose = skip)
\`\`\`

### Sprocket/Pulley Alignment
Misalignment causes:
- Belt: tracking to one side, premature wear, jumping
- Chain: side loading on bearings, skipping, wear

Always use a straightedge across pulleys/sprockets to verify alignment.

### Calculating Belt Length
\`\`\`
Belt links = 2×(center distance/pitch) + (T1+T2)/2
Round UP to nearest even number
\`\`\`

### Calculating Chain Links
Same formula, pitch = 6.35mm (#25 chain) or 9.525mm (#35)
