      {id:"ja16",title:"Advanced Auto Paths with Spline Math",est:"35 min",content:`## Cubic Hermite Splines for Smooth Paths

Understanding the math behind Road Runner's paths helps you design better autonomous routines.

### Why Splines?
Straight lines connected by point turns are inefficient. Splines create smooth curves that the robot follows at full speed, without stopping to reorient.

### Cubic Hermite Spline Definition
A cubic Hermite spline between two points is defined by:
- Start position and tangent (direction + magnitude)
- End position and tangent

\`\`\`java
// Math representation
// p(t) = h00(t)*p0 + h10(t)*m0 + h01(t)*p1 + h11(t)*m1
// where t goes 0→1, h00/h10/h01/h11 are basis functions
// p0, p1 = endpoints (x,y)
// m0, m1 = tangent vectors at each endpoint

// Hermite basis functions:
// h00(t) = 2t³ - 3t² + 1
// h10(t) = t³ - 2t² + t
// h01(t) = -2t³ + 3t²
// h11(t) = t³ - t²
\`\`\`

### Practical Spline Use in Road Runner
\`\`\`java
// splineTo(endPos, endTangent)
// endTangent = direction the robot is heading when it arrives
drive.trajectoryBuilder(new Pose2d(0, 0, 0))
    // Curve from (0,0) facing 0° to (30,20) facing 90°
    .splineTo(new Vector2d(30, 20), Math.toRadians(90))
    // Continue curve to (50, 30) facing 0°
    .splineTo(new Vector2d(50, 30), Math.toRadians(0))
    .build();
\`\`\`

### Tangent Tuning Strategy
\`\`\`
Problem: Path goes wide and hits field element
Fix:     Adjust tangent at the waypoint to change curve shape

Sharper curve → lower tangent magnitude
Wider curve   → higher tangent magnitude
\`\`\`

### Path vs. Trajectory
| Type | Speed Profile | Use When |
|------|-------------|---------|
| Path | Normalized (unit speed) | Shape definition only |
| Trajectory | Time-parameterized | Actual robot execution |
| TrajectorySequence | Multi-segment + actions | Full auto routine |

### Constraint Tuning for Speed
\`\`\`java
TrajectoryVelocityConstraint velConstraint = 
    SampleMecanumDrive.getVelocityConstraint(
        40,  // Max velocity (in/s) — increase for faster auto
        Math.toRadians(180), // Max angular velocity
        DriveConstants.TRACK_WIDTH
    );

TrajectoryAccelerationConstraint accelConstraint =
    SampleMecanumDrive.getAccelerationConstraint(30); // in/s²
\`\`\`
