      {id:"mi14",title:"Linear Motion Systems",est:"24 min",content:`## Linear Actuators and Slides

Linear motion (extending up, out, or sideways) is one of the most common robot functions — lifts, slides, and arms.

### Types of Linear Systems

**Linear Slides (Cascade/Continuous)**
- Nested aluminum extrusion sections
- Driven by string, cable, or belt
- REV 15mm, Misumi, GoBILDA slides are common in FTC
- Cascade: all stages extend simultaneously (fast, one motor)
- Continuous: stages extend sequentially (slower, more stages possible)

**Lead Screw**
- Motor turns threaded rod, nut translates rotation to linear
- Very high mechanical advantage
- Self-locking (holds position without power)
- Slow — good for precise positioning
- FTC use: arm rotation, slow precise lifts

**Rack and Pinion**
- Gear (pinion) rolls along toothed bar (rack)
- Linear, fast, backdrivable
- FTC use: horizontal extension

### Rigging String/Cable Systems
\`\`\`
Motor spool → string → redirect pulley → slide end

Key rules:
1. String parallel to slide = no side load on bearings
2. Equal string length on both sides (if dual-strung)
3. Knot or knotless ferrule — never rely on tape
4. Travel limiter (hard stop) prevents over-extension
\`\`\`

### Speed vs Extension Length
\`\`\`
Motor: 312 RPM, spool diameter = 1"
Spool circumference = π × 1 = 3.14"
Extension rate = 312 × 3.14" / 60 = 16.3 inches/second

For a 4-stage cascade slide:
  Each stage extends 8" → 32" total travel
  At 16.3"/s → full extension in ~0.5 seconds ✓ Fast!
\`\`\`

### Common Failure Points
- **String breaks** → use 80+ lb braided fishing line or Spectra cord
- **String slips off spool** → add string guide or flanged spool
- **Slide binds** → check alignment, reduce preload, add lubrication (dry PTFE spray)
- **Over-extends** → add magnetic limit switch or encoder limit in code
