      {id:"ei10",title:"Debugging Electronics Problems",est:"20 min",content:`## Systematic Electronics Debugging

When your robot doesn't work, a systematic approach finds the problem 10× faster than random guessing.

### The Debugging Mindset
Stop assuming. Start measuring.

A motor that "doesn't work" could be:
- Dead motor
- Dead motor controller  
- Broken wire
- Loose connector
- Wrong port in config
- Wrong name in code
- Wrong RunMode

Test each possibility in order from easiest to hardest.

### The FTC Diagnostic Flow
\`\`\`
Symptom: Motor not responding
│
├─ Check Driver Hub: any errors? → Fix the error shown
├─ Check LED on motor controller → blinking = no signal, solid = fault
├─ Check Robot Config: is motor name correct?
│   └─ Rename in config to match code
├─ Test in Driver Hub "Manage" → Motor Test
│   ├─ Motor responds → problem is in your code
│   └─ Motor silent → problem is hardware
│       ├─ Swap motor port on hub → still dead? Hub is bad
│       └─ Works on other port → original port is dead
└─ Swap motor itself → motor is dead if still silent
\`\`\`

### Common FTC Error Messages
| Error | Cause | Fix |
|-------|-------|-----|
| "Unable to find hardware device" | Config name doesn't match code | Match config name exactly |
| "Failed to open servo controller" | Servo port mismatch | Check port number |
| "EMERGENCY STOP" | Java exception in code | Check logcat for stack trace |
| LED blinks red fast | Hardware fault / short circuit | Disconnect, inspect wiring |

### Using Telemetry as a Debugger
