      {id:"sfi3",title:"Robot Power-Up and Power-Down Safety",est:"15 min",content:`## Safe Power Procedures — Every Time, No Exceptions

More robots are damaged during power-up and power-down than during actual operation. These procedures prevent that.

### Pre-Power-Up Checklist
Before connecting the battery or flipping the power switch:
\`\`\`
□ Is everyone's hands clear of all mechanisms?
□ Is the robot on the ground or secured on a stand?
□ Are all covers/guards in place?
□ Have you announced "POWERING UP" to the workspace?
□ Is the area around the robot clear (3-foot radius)?
□ Are wheels blocked if on an inclined surface?
□ Is the battery connector in good condition (no cracks, burns)?
\`\`\`

### Power-Up Sequence (FTC)
1. Place robot in known safe position (not aimed at people)
2. Announce: **"Powering up — stand clear!"**
3. Connect battery cable (XT30 connector)
4. Flip main power switch
5. Wait 3 seconds before sending any commands
6. Test communications: verify Driver Hub shows green connection
7. Only then: slowly test each mechanism at low power

### Power-Down Sequence
1. Stop all motors and servos (set power to 0)
2. Flip main power switch OFF
3. Disconnect battery cable
4. Confirm robot is fully de-energized (check for any motion)
5. **Only then**: reach into or handle mechanisms

### Why Wait After Powering Up
Motor controllers and the Control Hub take 2-3 seconds to initialize. If you send commands before they're ready, the robot may behave unpredictably — jerking, full-speed movement, or ignoring commands entirely.

### Emergency Stop Procedures
**Robot moves unexpectedly:**
→ IMMEDIATELY flip main power switch
→ Stay AWAY from moving mechanisms
→ Do not try to grab or stop moving parts by hand

**Wire smokes or sparks:**
→ Flip power switch → disconnect battery
→ Do not use water — use CO2 or dry chemical extinguisher
→ Alert all team members and mentors

**Someone is caught in mechanism:**
→ Cut power immediately (switch or battery disconnect)
→ Do NOT reverse the mechanism — stop first, assess, then carefully reverse
