      {id:"sfb2",title:"Electrical Safety Basics",est:"14 min",content:`## Electrical Safety for FIRST Robots

Robots run on 12V batteries — that's enough to cause serious burns and fire. Take it seriously.

### Battery Safety
\`\`\`
FTC: 12V LiPo (3 cells)
FRC: 12V SLA (Sealed Lead Acid)

Danger levels:
• Short circuit (direct + to -): FIRE, explosion risk
• Overcharge: Battery swells, vents toxic gas
• Physical damage: LiPo WILL catch fire if punctured
• Wrong charger: LiPo REQUIRES LiPo-specific charger
\`\`\`

### Non-Negotiable Rules
- **Always** connect battery to robot before turning on robot
- **Never** reverse battery polarity (swap + and -) — destroys electronics instantly
- **Never** leave charging batteries unattended
- **Never** charge a puffy/swollen LiPo — it must be disposed of properly
- **Always** use the main switch to cut power before working on robot
- **Always** have a fire extinguisher accessible when using LiPo batteries

### Wiring Best Practices
| Rule | Why |
|------|-----|
| Fuse or breaker on every positive wire | Prevents overload fire |
| No bare wire ends exposed | Short circuit risk |
| Secure all wiring away from moving parts | Abrasion causes shorts |
| Use wire of correct gauge | Undersized wire overheats |
| Red = positive, Black = ground | Universal convention, prevents mistakes |

### What to Do If a LiPo Catches Fire
1. **Do NOT use water** — makes lithium fires worse
2. Use a Class D fire extinguisher OR smother with sand
3. Move away — burning LiPo releases toxic fumes
4. Call for help immediately
5. Do NOT breathe the smoke

### Inspection Tips
Before every session, check:
- Battery connector for cracks, corrosion, or heat marks
- All wire connections secure (no loose crimp terminals)
- No exposed copper anywhere in the wiring
- Battery voltage before use (FTC LiPo: 12.6V full, warn at 11.0V)
