      {id:"mbN1",title:"3D Printing for Robots",est:"20 min",content:`## FDM 3D Printing for FIRST Robots

3D printing is a superpower for FIRST teams — make custom brackets in hours, not days.

### Common Materials
| Material | Strength | Flex | Heat | Best For |
|----------|----------|------|------|----------|
| PLA | Medium | Low | Low (60°C) | Prototypes, covers |
| PETG | Good | Some | Medium (80°C) | Functional parts |
| TPU | Low | High | Medium | Bumpers, grips |
| ASA/ABS | Good | Low | High | Outdoor, heat areas |
| Nylon PA12 | Excellent | Some | High | Gears, load-bearing |

**FTC/FRC Rule:** Printed parts are legal if they don't violate other rules (sharp edges, weight limits, etc.)

### Print Settings That Matter
\`\`\`
Layer Height: 0.2mm — good balance of strength and speed
             0.1mm — stronger, much slower
Infill:       20% — covers/aesthetics
             40% — most functional parts
             60%+ — gears, high-stress brackets
Walls:        2 shells — light parts
              4 shells — structural parts
              6+ shells — critical load-bearing
Orientation:  CRITICAL — layers are weak in tension perpendicular to them
\`\`\`

### Designing for Printing
\`\`\`
✅ DO:
- Orient so loads run parallel to layers (not perpendicular)
- Add fillets (0.5-2mm) to reduce stress concentrations
- Use hex nuts + heat inserts for threaded connections
- Design 0.2mm clearance for press-fit holes
- Wall thickness: minimum 1.5mm for FDM

❌ DON'T:
- Print gears in PLA (use Nylon or buy metal)
- Use supports if you can avoid with good design
- Trust prints near motors (heat!)
- Print holes smaller than 3mm without drilling
\`\`\`

### Key Robotics Applications
- **Custom brackets:** Mount cameras, sensors at any angle
- **Cable guides:** Route wires cleanly through the robot
- **Intake wheels:** TPU for compliant surface (soft on game pieces)
- **Gear covers:** Protect drivetrain gears from debris
- **Jigs and fixtures:** Consistency when drilling or bending
