      {id:"maN1",title:"Drivetrain Selection Deep Dive",est:"28 min",content:`## Choosing the Right Drivetrain

Your drivetrain choice fundamentally shapes your robot's capabilities. This is the most important mechanical decision of build season.

### Comparison Matrix
| Drivetrain | Agility | Pushing | Speed | Complexity | Cost |
|------------|---------|---------|-------|------------|------|
| Tank | Low | ★★★★★ | ★★★ | Low | Low |
| West Coast | Medium | ★★★★ | ★★★★ | Medium | Medium |
| Mecanum | ★★★★ | ★★ | ★★★ | Medium | Medium |
| Swerve | ★★★★★ | ★★★ | ★★★★★ | Very High | High |
| H-Drive | ★★★ | ★★ | ★★★ | Medium | Medium |

### When to Choose Each
**Tank Drive:**
- Best for: Defense-heavy games, pushing matches, beginners
- Weakness: Can't strafe — must turn to realign

**Mecanum (FTC/FRC):**
- Best for: Games requiring precise lateral movement, tight spaces
- Weakness: Less pushing force, wheels wear fast, slips on carpet
- Math: All 4 wheels run simultaneously at different speeds

**Swerve (FRC mostly):**
- Best for: Highest-level competition, speed + agility
- Weakness: Complex maintenance, expensive, requires great programmers
- Avoid if: First year, small team, limited programming experience

### Gear Ratio Selection
\`\`\`
Target speed calculation:
Free speed of motor (RPM) ÷ Gear ratio = Wheel RPM
Wheel RPM × Wheel circumference = Robot speed

Example (NEO motor on FRC mecanum):
5880 RPM ÷ 8.46:1 gear ratio = 695 wheel RPM
695 RPM × (4" wheel × π / 12) = 14.5 ft/s ≈ 4.4 m/s

FRC typical target: 10-16 ft/s (3-5 m/s)
FTC typical target: 2-4 ft/s (0.6-1.2 m/s)
\`\`\`

### Wheel Selection
- **6" colson/plaction (FRC):** Durable, good traction, standard
- **4" mecanum (FRC/FTC):** Lateral movement, less traction
- **4" omni + 2" standard (FTC):** Dead-wheel odometry setup
- **90mm goBILDA mecanum (FTC):** Easy mounting, proven design

### Build Quality Factors
A well-built simple drivetrain beats a poorly-built complex one every time:
1. Parallel wheel alignment (< 1mm variance)
2. Chain/belt tension (not too tight, not loose)
3. Proper bearing press-fits
4. Ground clearance > 0.5" to avoid carpet drag
