      {id:"ebN1",title:"FRC Electrical System Walkthrough",est:"22 min",content:`## FRC Electrical System: Every Component

FRC robots have strict electrical rules. Understanding every component prevents inspection failures and fires.

### Power Flow
\`\`\`
Battery (12V, 18Ah)
  ↓ (main breaker — master power switch)
Power Distribution Hub (PDH) or PDP
  ↓ (fused outputs — each circuit has its own breaker)
Motor Controllers, Radio, roboRIO
  ↓
Motors, Solenoids, Sensors
\`\`\`

### Required Components
| Component | Purpose | Rule |
|-----------|---------|------|
| Main Breaker | Emergency power cutoff | Must be accessible, red/button type |
| PDH/PDP | Distributes power, fuses circuits | One per robot |
| roboRIO | Main computer | FRC2 only for competition |
| RSL (Robot Signal Light) | Shows robot state | Blinking = enabled |
| Radio | WiFi link to driver station | Must use FRC radio |
| Battery | 12V, 18Ah minimum | NPC/MK or approved brands |

### Motor Controller Rules
- Each motor needs its own motor controller
- FRC-approved: Victor SPX, SPARK MAX, Talon SRX, Falcon 500 built-in
- All controllers to CAN bus OR PWM (not mixed on same controller)
- Current limit: set in software to protect motors

### Wiring Best Practices
\`\`\`
✅ Power wires: red=positive, black=negative (ALWAYS)
✅ Fuse every circuit appropriately (40A drivetrain, 20-30A arm, 10A small)
✅ Strain relief: never let wires pull on connectors
✅ Separate power and signal wires (noise reduction)
✅ Anderson Powerpole connectors for main power
✅ Label every wire — saves hours at competition

❌ Never: bare wire exposed anywhere
❌ Never: wire gauges too small (20A circuit → minimum 18AWG)
❌ Never: skip the main breaker
\`\`\`

### The RSL Signal Light
Rapid blink = robot enabled and receiving commands ⚡
Slow blink = robot on, not enabled
Solid = communications error or e-stop
